[In the past 24 hours, according to the report at the source URL, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 51 cases with no new deaths, compared with 43 cases and no new deaths in the previous day (29 Jun 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 80 consecutive days. There were 36 locally transmitted cases: Gwangju (12), Gyeonggi (11), Seoul (9), Daejeon (3), and Daegu (1); and 15 imported cases -- airport quarantine (5), Gyeonggi (5), Incheon (2), Daejeon (1), Chungnam (1), and Jeonnam (1). There were 9 provinces reporting no newly confirmed cases.

According to data from the "ncov" website of the Ministry of Health and Welfare, the cumulative confirmation rate has been 1.0% (http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/).

The overall impression hasn't changed: Lifting of measures has been accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship, and bars and clubs. But, that being said, importations are also playing a major role in the country. It would be nice to know the asymptomatic rate being detected, and the proportion of asymptomatic infections detected that go on to clinical disease.

Tabular and graphic analyses of the situation in South Korea with the addition of the 43 newly confirmed cases from 29 Jun 2020 are available at the English language page (<https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030), notices 405 and 406. There are analyses of the country-wide situation including the newly confirmed cases including listings of current ongoing clusters. 4 of the clusters mentioned are related to religious gatherings, and 1 related to a family gathering (the same as the previous day).

Importations came from Americas (3), Europe (1), Africa (2), Asia excluding China (14), (Kazakhstan 10, Pakistan 2, Afghanistan 1, and Kuwait 1).

Takeaway message: Importations continue to be a challenge, and gatherings whether social or religious are key foci for enlarging clusters (unchanged from previous 2 day's message).

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7528543,195. - Mod.MPP]

