[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update (please note that there has been consistent weekend reporting artifact since the presentation of these data began):
-----------------------------------------
The Americas region reported 57.5% of the global newly reported cases and 59.2% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period. The USA reported 43.5% of the newly confirmed cases in the region, and Brazil reported 32.3%, Mexico and Chile 4.3%, Peru 3.6%, Colombia 3.4%, and Argentina 2.3%. The same 5 countries remained at the top; the USA and Brazil are usually numbers 1 and 2, although they vary for which of the 2 positions they hold, but other countries are continuing to increase their proportional representation within the region.

The European region reported 11.5% of the global newly reported cases and 10.5% of the newly confirmed deaths in the region. Russia reported 35.5% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Sweden 13.4%, Turkey 7.3%, the UK 4.3%, France 4.1%, Ukraine 3.7%, Azerbaijan 2.9%, Kazakhstan and Germany 2.6%, and Armenia 2.2%. The proportion of cases represented by Russia continues to decrease. Sweden did not report any newly confirmed cases yesterday (29 Jun 2020) so I suspect the major increase may be weekend delayed reporting. Armenia, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan, and Ukraine are prominent in countries noted to have resurgence in Europe. The reappearance of Germany and France on this highlighted list (more than 2.0%) also bears watching.

The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 9.9% of the global newly reported cases and 13.6% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 24.2%, of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Pakistan 17.4%, Iran 15.6%, Iraq 10.7%, Egypt 9.6%, Oman 5.6%, Qatar 4.3%, and Kuwait 3.6%. Multiple countries are very active in the region -- same countries in the same order as yesterday (29 Jun 2020).

The African region reported 5.5% of the global newly reported cases and 3.3% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 68.5% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Nigeria 6.3%, Algeria 3.3%, Mauritania 2.7%, and Gabon 2.1%. Other countries of prior prominence are less than 2%. South Africa and Nigeria are usually numbers 1 and 2 (although Ghana surpassed Nigeria yesterday 29 Jun 2020, but didn't report any cases today) in terms of the 24-hour increase in cases, other countries have less consistent reporting patterns and vary considerably from day to day.

The Western Pacific region reported 0.89% of the global newly reported cases and 0.28% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 67.3% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Singapore 13.8%, Japan 8.0%, Australia 5.5%, South Korea 2.9%, and China 1.6%. The outbreak associated with the Beijing seafood markets continues to bring China to prominence in terms of daily newly confirmed cases. That said, the Philippines and Singapore are consistently numbers 1 and 2, respectively, and the other countries, including Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, and Australia, vary in daily reporting, although today's ordering is identical to yesterday's.

The South East Asia region reported 14.7% of the global newly reported cases and 13.1% of global deaths. India reported 76.8% of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 16.6%, Indonesia 4.5%, and Nepal 2.0%. Same countries, same order as in previous days, with India continuing to be the driving force in the regional growth in cases.

Impression: The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis, followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe and the Eastern Mediterranean alternating on a daily basis of their order, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily case load of all of the regions. There is still weekend artifact with prominent countries not reporting any cases and others reporting probable backlog from the weekend.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 30 Jun 2020, at the source URL above, is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. The Americas region continues to increase, as does South-East Asia, in terms of daily newly confirmed cases; the African region is noticeably increasing as well. The Americas region continues to greatly outnumber all other regions for daily reporting. - Mod.MPP]

